description.narrative: (Malawi): To support self-reliance and ensure democratic accountability, Malawian civil society organizations (CSOs) must have the necessary institutional capabilities to implement their work and engage effectively on public issues. STEPS is building the capacity of over 30 Malawian organizations to enhance their leadership and strategic management, financial management and fundraising, human resources, program management, and communications so they can deliver quality services and advocate for their constituencies. The Joint Strategic Plan notes that working with civil society groups is an important part of promoting healthy, educated, productive populations and of mobilizing support and resources to shape foreign public opinion. ..With FY18 funds, STEPS will complete training and mentoring activities to address CSO organizational needs identified through the annual capacity assessment process. This will include improving board governance and oversight, financial management, and strategic planning. STEPS will determine which CSOs are eligible for "graduation" and support an alumni and legacy institution that will provide free online and fee-for-service tailored training to enable continued assistance after project closure. The project will also support up to eight new CSOs which will have recently received grants through the Local works program and pair them with stronger CSOs to facilitate learning. Progress will be rigorously measured through self and external assessments. .STEPS will help Parliament improve its legislative and oversight functions. It will help establish a Parliamentary Budget Office and strengthen Parliament's research capabilities to help Members of Parliament contribute more effectively to the policy-making process and improve oversight of public finances and government business. Civil society organizations will help provide information to committees, thus advancing CSOs' advocacy and evidence-based policy. ....
